one of the snow globes.

278
00:11:07,550 --> 00:11:10,552
But which one?
Ooh, I don't know.

279
00:11:13,206 --> 00:11:16,024
Nope. No.

280
00:11:16,059 --> 00:11:18,360
No. You really suck at this.
Okay, why don't you just...

281
00:11:18,378 --> 00:11:19,494
Tell me where it is
and I can get out of here?

282
00:11:19,528 --> 00:11:21,196
That would take
all the fun out of it.

283
00:11:21,231 --> 00:11:23,365
- Ah!
- Winner.

284
00:11:23,399 --> 00:11:25,033
Ah, ha, ha, ha.
I found it.

285
00:11:25,068 --> 00:11:27,369
Yep. Oh, wait.

286
00:11:27,403 --> 00:11:29,371
No, that might be
from another scavenger hunt.

287
00:11:29,389 --> 00:11:32,341
Ann, looks like
you already met Jeff.

288
00:11:32,375 --> 00:11:34,542
Well, you didn't tell me that
your friend was so beautiful.

289
00:11:34,561 --> 00:11:36,111
Aww, thanks, Jeff.

290
00:11:36,145 --> 00:11:37,779
Not as beautiful
as my sister,

291
00:11:37,814 --> 00:11:40,115
but you know the law.

292
00:11:40,149 --> 00:11:41,917
- What?
- No, Jeff.

293
00:11:41,951 --> 00:11:44,570
How am I supposed
to find the love of Ann's life

294
00:11:44,604 --> 00:11:45,938
when it sounds
like a funeral in here?

295
00:11:45,989 --> 00:11:48,290
There's no changing it
as long as Chris is depressed.

296
00:11:48,324 --> 00:11:50,108
I'm gonna go talk to Chris.
You go help Ann.

297
00:11:50,159 --> 00:11:51,760
She's not responding
to my top candidates,

298
00:11:51,794 --> 00:11:53,579
so we're gonna have
to go with some wild cards.

299
00:11:53,613 --> 00:11:54,630
- Got it.
- And April...

300
00:11:54,664 --> 00:11:56,081
Thanks for nothing.

301
00:11:56,115 --> 00:11:57,282
Why should I do anything
to help her?

302
00:11:57,333 --> 00:11:58,901
Because despite the fact
that all you do

303
00:11:58,935 --> 00:12:01,570
is give her a hard time,
she would do this for you.

304
00:12:01,604 --> 00:12:04,139
Just go hide under the table
with your friend Orin.

305
00:12:04,173 --> 00:12:06,074
Yeah, I see you, weirdo.

306
00:12:08,811 --> 00:12:10,578
So Leslie dragged you

307
00:12:10,597 --> 00:12:12,814
into this sneaky little
fix-up scheme, huh?

308
00:12:12,849 --> 00:12:15,383
We're stuck at a Parks and Rec
community couples event.

309
00:12:15,418 --> 00:12:16,884
What else
you gotta do?

310
00:12:16,919 --> 00:12:18,854
What the hell.
You're right.

311
00:12:18,888 --> 00:12:19,938
Bring 'em on, Tom.

312
00:12:19,973 --> 00:12:22,090
I'm Harris.
Heard you were desperate

313
00:12:22,125 --> 00:12:24,726
for a man-piece.
We in business?

314
00:12:24,761 --> 00:12:27,462
He's 33 years old,
still lives with his parents,

315
00:12:27,497 --> 00:12:30,599
and he's been to at least
200 Phish concerts.

316
00:12:30,633 --> 00:12:32,334
Try 308.

317
00:12:32,368 --> 00:12:33,635
I'm gonna have
to pass right now.

318
00:12:33,670 --> 00:12:35,070
Your mistake, mama.

319
00:12:35,104 --> 00:12:39,875
So, Bill, this stunning woman
saves lives for a living.

320
00:12:39,909 --> 00:12:41,243
What do you
bring to the table?

321
00:12:41,277 --> 00:12:43,512
Uh, where to begin?
Uh, I'm an amateur juggler...

322
00:12:43,546 --> 00:12:44,779
Nope, you shouldn't
have begun there.

323
00:12:44,797 --> 00:12:47,949
Get out. No one's trying
to get with jugglers.

324
00:12:47,967 --> 00:12:49,835
Thanks for playing.

325
00:12:56,893 --> 00:12:59,728
Hello, my name
is Ron Swanson.

326
00:12:59,762 --> 00:13:02,297
I believe Leslie Knope
may have left some kind

327
00:13:02,315 --> 00:13:03,865
of scavenger hunt
clue here.

328
00:13:03,900 --> 00:13:06,268
She did.
One second.

329
00:13:11,188 --> 00:13:12,307
Gentlemen.

330
00:13:13,325 --> 00:13:15,178
Ah-.

331
00:13:15,325 --> 00:13:16,378
Enjoy your evening.

332
00:13:18,412 --> 00:13:22,430
Well... it always says
"Break glass in case of an emergency."

333
00:13:24,486 --> 00:13:25,287
Wait a second.

334
00:13:28,541 --> 00:13:33,178
Well, there we go.

335
00:13:33,212 --> 00:13:35,830
Hey, Chris, what do you think
about changing the music?

336
00:13:35,848 --> 00:13:39,534
Sure.

337
00:13:39,569 --> 00:13:40,886
Ugh. Hey,
you know what?

338
00:13:40,937 --> 00:13:42,604
You should look
on the bright side.

339
00:13:42,638 --> 00:13:44,606
I'm sure that Millicent
couldn't keep up with you

340
00:13:44,640 --> 00:13:47,476
on your runs, so now
you can go full speed again.

341
00:13:47,510 --> 00:13:50,479
On the contrary,
she was faster than I was.

342
00:13:50,513 --> 00:13:54,483
I set many personal bests
just trying to keep up with her.

343
00:13:54,517 --> 00:13:57,285
Which is what
I'm worried about.

344
00:13:57,320 --> 00:14:00,255
What if she was
my personal best?

345
00:14:00,289 --> 00:14:02,591
No, your best
is still ahead of you.

346
00:14:02,625 --> 00:14:04,860
I am 44 years old.

347
00:14:04,894 --> 00:14:06,261
You don't look
a day over 30.

348
00:14:06,295 --> 00:14:07,562
Most people say 25.

349
00:14:07,597 --> 00:14:09,197
- Who says that?
- Lot of people.

350
00:14:09,232 --> 00:14:11,767
You don't think that
Millicent was my soul mate?

351
00:14:11,801 --> 00:14:13,969
There are a lot
of soul mates in the world.

352
00:14:14,003 --> 00:14:15,303
I mean, look at Ann.

353
00:14:15,338 --> 00:14:17,572
You dated her, and she's
a perfect human specimen,

354
00:14:17,607 --> 00:14:19,941
and you tossed her out
like day-old chowder.

355
00:14:19,976 --> 00:14:22,010
But it's
gonna be okay.

356
00:14:22,044 --> 00:14:23,011
Buck up.

357
00:14:23,045 --> 00:14:26,014
Thanks, I'll try.

358
00:14:36,092 --> 00:14:38,393
♪

359
00:14:38,411 --> 00:14:40,412
- Hey.
- Hey.

360
00:14:40,446 --> 00:14:41,780
How is your
evening unfolding

361
00:14:41,831 --> 00:14:43,248
in terms of your
conversations with men?

362
00:14:43,282 --> 00:14:45,417
I have met a lot
of different guys tonight.

363
00:14:45,451 --> 00:14:48,286
How lucky that
that happened to you

364
00:14:48,337 --> 00:14:50,672
- on Valentine's Day.
- What's lucky

365
00:14:50,706 --> 00:14:53,642
is that I have a best friend
who spent her Valentine's Day

366
00:14:53,676 --> 00:14:54,643
trying to find
me a date.

367
00:14:54,677 --> 00:14:56,678
Thank you.
I'm gonna go home.

368
00:14:56,712 --> 00:14:58,180
No. Stay.

369
00:14:58,214 --> 00:15:00,215
I just... I'm gonna
go home and watch TV.

370
00:15:00,249 --> 00:15:02,317
Okay, well,
can you just do me a favor

371
00:15:02,351 --> 00:15:03,652
and give me your car keys
for a second?

372
00:15:03,686 --> 00:15:05,487
There's something I need
to look at on your car keys.

373
00:15:05,521 --> 00:15:07,022
You're gonna throw them
on the roof again

374
00:15:07,056 --> 00:15:08,890
- so I can't leave.
- You know me too well.

375
00:15:08,924 --> 00:15:12,477
You're the best.

376
00:15:12,528 --> 00:15:14,762
It sucks being alone
on Valentine's Day,

377
00:15:14,781 --> 00:15:17,165
so I'm gonna take Ann out
for a drink, you know.

378
00:15:17,200 --> 00:15:20,435
Try to cheer her up.
And I can be late meeting Ben.

379
00:15:20,453 --> 00:15:23,972
He's not gonna be on time,
'cause those clues are hard.

380
00:15:24,006 --> 00:15:26,408
They're really, really hard,
and I'm really worried

381
00:15:26,442 --> 00:15:28,677
that he's not gonna be able
to figure it out.

382
00:15:35,951 --> 00:15:38,220
Ann, you tricky bastard.

383
00:15:38,254 --> 00:15:40,622
- Leslie, what are you doing?
- Look at Ann.

384
00:15:40,656 --> 00:15:43,391
She's putting on makeup.
She using the emergency

385
00:15:43,426 --> 00:15:44,726
mini curling iron
that I gave her.

386
00:15:44,760 --> 00:15:47,012
- She has a date.
- You don't know that.

387
00:15:47,063 --> 00:15:49,664
Why wouldn't
she tell me who it is?

388
00:15:50,199 --> 00:15:50,966
Because she doesn't
want me to know.

389
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:53,301
Because it's someone
she shouldn't be dating.

390
00:15:53,336 --> 00:15:55,971
Wait, the music's better.
Have you seen Chris?

391
00:15:56,005 --> 00:15:57,906
I don't know, maybe he's
in the bathroom or something.

392
00:15:59,440 --> 00:16:01,009
She's going
to meet Chris.

393
00:16:05,404 --> 00:16:08,091
Hey, I got nine,
three and four.

394
00:16:08,404 --> 00:16:12,491
I have 11, 12, 13, 14,
15, 16, 17, 18, and 19.

395
00:16:12,525 --> 00:16:13,558
Whoa.

396
00:16:13,593 --> 00:16:15,243
I got...
I got lucky.

397
00:16:15,294 --> 00:16:17,396
And I love riddles.

398
00:16:17,430 --> 00:16:21,466
Yo, found some clues.
Also found this.

399
00:16:21,501 --> 00:16:23,702
Weird stick.
Might be a clue.

400
00:16:23,736 --> 00:16:25,170
- No.
- Okay.

401
00:16:25,204 --> 00:16:27,072
Did you find
the 25th clue?

402
00:16:27,106 --> 00:16:29,341
No, I got #8,
and #22.

403
00:16:31,394 --> 00:16:32,547
434

404
00:16:34,394 --> 00:16:35,547
What do you want, April?

405
00:16:35,581 --> 00:16:37,416
Leave Ann alone.
This is none of your business.

406
00:16:37,450 --> 00:16:39,951
After all the hoops that
Ben and I had to jump through

407
00:16:39,986 --> 00:16:41,753
because of the
boss-employee thing,

408
00:16:41,788 --> 00:16:43,655
it is absolutely
my business.

409
00:16:43,689 --> 00:16:47,559
Chris needs to explain himself,
and Ann lied to me

410
00:16:47,593 --> 00:16:50,912
about this date.
I mean, so many injustices.

411
00:16:50,947 --> 00:16:53,498
Ann would never do anything
to piss you off, Leslie.

412
00:16:53,533 --> 00:16:55,700
You guys are such
close friends, it's lame.

413
00:16:55,734 --> 00:16:58,103
Just have a nice night with Ben,
and forget about this.

414
00:16:58,137 --> 00:17:01,873
Okay, fine.
I will let it go for now.

415
00:17:01,908 --> 00:17:03,875
But I want you to know
that I think there is some...

416
00:17:03,909 --> 00:17:06,044
[beep]

417
00:17:06,078 --> 00:17:07,748
Okay, she hung up on me.

418
00:17:09,782 --> 00:17:11,716
We failed.

419
00:17:11,751 --> 00:17:13,635
If I just had
a little more time.

420
00:17:13,686 --> 00:17:15,587
She's waiting for me
somewhere in Pawnee,

421
00:17:15,605 --> 00:17:17,939
- and I'm not gonna be there.
- Wait...

422
00:17:17,974 --> 00:17:20,759
Leslie loves romance,
but she also loves being right.

423
00:17:20,793 --> 00:17:23,495
Is there something you used
to disagree on,

424
00:17:23,529 --> 00:17:25,564
but you've since come around
to her way of thinking?

425
00:17:27,098 --> 00:17:28,783
Ron, you're a genius.

426
00:17:33,272 --> 00:17:34,789
Little Sebastian.

427
00:17:34,824 --> 00:17:36,441
At first you
did not understand

428
00:17:36,476 --> 00:17:38,877
what made this
tiny horse so special,

429
00:17:38,911 --> 00:17:40,111
and now you love him
more than I do.

430
00:17:40,129 --> 00:17:43,048
Yep, I miss him
every day.

431
00:17:43,082 --> 00:17:45,050
I really tried
to make that hard.

432
00:17:45,084 --> 00:17:46,651
I'm very impressed
with you.

433
00:17:46,686 --> 00:17:48,019
Eh, some of them
were kind of tough.

434
00:17:48,054 --> 00:17:50,021
So are you ready to go

435
00:17:50,056 --> 00:17:51,990
have our first ever
Valentine's dinner?

436
00:17:52,024 --> 00:17:53,859
Yes, but I have
to tell you something.

437
00:17:53,893 --> 00:17:57,128
Chris and Ann
are on a secret date.

438
00:17:57,163 --> 00:17:59,331
Which is crazy
because he's her boss,

439
00:17:59,365 --> 00:18:01,032
which is the exact
situation we were in,

440
00:18:01,067 --> 00:18:03,435
except we were put
on trial for it.

441
00:18:03,469 --> 00:18:04,436
And I know I'm not
supposed to care,

442
00:18:04,470 --> 00:18:05,537
and I'm supposed
to let it go,

443
00:18:05,571 --> 00:18:07,305
and we should just
have a romantic dinner...

444
00:18:07,323 --> 00:18:09,207
No, we have to go
catch them in the act.

445
00:18:09,242 --> 00:18:10,709
- Right now.
- Really?

446
00:18:10,743 --> 00:18:13,028
Yeah. Screw
romantic dinners.

447
00:18:13,079 --> 00:18:14,613
Let's go rub it
in their face.

448
00:18:14,647 --> 00:18:16,781
God, I love you
so much.

449
00:18:16,815 --> 00:18:18,816
I cannot wait
to see the look

450
00:18:18,834 --> 00:18:20,985
on Chris' remarkably
youthful face

451
00:18:21,003 --> 00:18:23,205
when we march in there
and confront him...

452
00:18:23,256 --> 00:18:24,890
Whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, Leslie.

453
00:18:27,510 --> 00:18:29,127
What?

454
00:18:29,161 --> 00:18:31,129
Ahh!

455
00:18:31,163 --> 00:18:32,130
Shh.

456
00:18:32,164 --> 00:18:34,165
- Shh.
- April.

457
00:18:34,183 --> 00:18:36,167
- Hey.
- April.

458
00:18:36,185 --> 00:18:38,703
- Tom and Ann are on a date.
- I know.

459
00:18:38,738 --> 00:18:40,338
What do you mean you know?
How do you know?

460
00:18:40,373 --> 00:18:44,175
Because...
I set them up.

461
00:18:45,373 --> 00:18:47,175
I was watching
Ann with Tom at the dance

462
00:18:47,573 --> 00:18:49,475
and she seemed to
be having a good time.

463
00:18:50,073 --> 00:18:51,475
So I went over
to talk to her.

464
00:18:52,084 --> 00:18:54,352
What are you looking for
in a date anyway?

465
00:18:54,370 --> 00:18:56,521
I don't know.
What does anyone want?

466
00:18:56,556 --> 00:19:01,259
Just a nice, funny guy
who likes me and treats me well.

467
00:19:01,294 --> 00:19:04,162
Tom's funny,
and he'd treat you well.

468
00:19:04,196 --> 00:19:07,432
- Ha, ha.
- I'm serious.

469
00:19:07,466 --> 00:19:08,900
You want a good date,
why not ask out

470
00:19:08,935 --> 00:19:11,002
the only guy that's
made you smile tonight?

471
00:19:11,037 --> 00:19:12,637
He's ridiculous.

472
00:19:12,672 --> 00:19:15,006
- All that dumb swagger.
- It's not.

473
00:19:15,041 --> 00:19:18,043
He's sweet. You should just
ask him out for a drink.

474
00:19:18,077 --> 00:19:20,579
I'm 1,000% sure
he'd say yes.

475
00:19:20,613 --> 00:19:23,181
I bet you guys
would have a good time.

476
00:19:23,215 --> 00:19:25,850
Man, I need to, like,
wrap my head around this.

477
00:19:25,885 --> 00:19:27,085
Why? It makes
sense to me.

478
00:19:27,119 --> 00:19:29,921
This is a small, loser town
with loser people,

479
00:19:29,956 --> 00:19:32,457
and Tom's, like,
at least semi-cool.

480
00:19:32,491 --> 00:19:33,792
You know
what I'm hearing?

481
00:19:34,526 --> 00:19:37,896
You tried to make Ann happy
for Valentine's Day.

482
00:19:37,930 --> 00:19:40,532
- Ugh.
- You're a very nice person.

483
00:19:40,566 --> 00:19:41,533
- No.
- Yes, you are.

484
00:19:41,567 --> 00:19:43,568
- Very nice person.
- Bye.

485
00:19:46,205 --> 00:19:48,590
I do not understand this.
This really confuses me.

486
00:19:48,624 --> 00:19:50,141
Well, you do
love them both.

487
00:19:50,176 --> 00:19:54,129
Yeah, I love passionate
speakers and Italian men.

488
00:19:54,180 --> 00:19:55,480
Doesn't mean
I love Mussolini.

489
00:19:55,514 --> 00:19:56,931
You love
Italian men?

490
00:19:56,966 --> 00:19:59,084
Not as much as...

491
00:19:59,118 --> 00:20:02,087
Irish... Scottish?

492
00:20:02,121 --> 00:20:05,557
White... whatever you are.

493
00:20:05,591 --> 00:20:08,293
This is the weirdest
Valentine's Day ever.

494
00:20:11,797 --> 00:20:15,099
So, Ann,
it's finally happening.

495
00:20:15,117 --> 00:20:17,102
Dude, this is so close
to falling apart.

496
00:20:17,136 --> 00:20:18,737
Okay, okay,
I'm sorry.

497
00:20:19,271 --> 00:20:22,657
Can I be honest, though?
I'm a little freaked out.

498
00:20:22,708 --> 00:20:25,343
Like, I don't really
understand what's going on.

499
00:20:25,878 --> 00:20:27,312
This is
what's going on...

500
00:20:27,346 --> 00:20:28,580
we're gonna
have a drink,

501
00:20:28,614 --> 00:20:31,950
and we're gonna talk,
get to know each other.

502
00:20:31,984 --> 00:20:35,086
And then I am going
to drive home... alone.

503
00:20:35,121 --> 00:20:37,088
Cool. Consider this
alternate plan...

504
00:20:37,122 --> 00:20:38,757
we have drinks here, get to know
each other, whatever.

505
00:20:38,791 --> 00:20:42,293
Then we go back to my place
and snuggle up...

506
00:20:42,328 --> 00:20:43,762
Like little bunnies.

507
00:20:43,796 --> 00:20:45,797
- Yeah, this was a mistake.
- No!

508
00:20:48,207 --> 00:20:51,059
Leslie, thanks to your
annoying prying last year,

509
00:20:51,093 --> 00:20:53,161
I'm sure you remember
my birthday's coming up.

510
00:20:53,195 --> 00:20:55,263
I know, I know.
No parties, you hate parties.

511
00:20:55,298 --> 00:20:57,799
Correct.

512
00:20:57,833 --> 00:21:00,669
Oh, you know that
wild goose chase

513
00:21:00,703 --> 00:21:02,337
you sent Ben on
for Valentine's Day?

514
00:21:02,871 --> 00:21:04,071
The scavenger hunt?

515
00:21:04,106 --> 00:21:07,675
- I also do not want that.
- Yep, I understand.

516
00:21:07,709 --> 00:21:10,044
I absolutely do not want
to solve a series

517
00:21:10,078 --> 00:21:13,214
of riddles and clues, each more
intricate than the last.

518
00:21:13,248 --> 00:21:14,215
You understand
what I'm saying?

519
00:21:14,249 --> 00:21:16,350
- Yeah, I got it, Ron.
- Good.

520
00:21:21,223 --> 00:21:25,076
Uh, I-I do want that.
Please do that for me.

